fostering myth in Dublin, or Igor Stravinsky starting over from nothing in Switzerland, Crispin interweaves biography, incisive literary analysis, and personal experience into a rich meditation on the complicated interactions of place, personality, and society that can make escape and reinvention such an attractive, even intoxicating proposition. Personal and profane, funny and fervent, The Dead Ladies Project ranges from the nineteenth century to the present, from historical figures to brand-new hangovers, in search, ultimately, of an answer to a bedrock question: How does a person decide how to live their life?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAliensxBiography. 0aCelebritiesxHomes and haunts. 0aCities and townsxPsychological aspects. 0aNoncitizensvBiography. 0aPlace (Philosophy) 0aPlace (Philosophy). 7aTravel / General.2bisacsh  aexile, expat, country of origin, rebel, rebellious, chicago, life story, berlin, germany, travel, wanderlust, american, america, united states, europe, global, international, wanderer, realistic, literature, literary, academic, scholarly, research, fieldwork, william james, reflection, essay, analysis, nora barnacle, trieste, english major, historical, maud gonne, revolution, myth, mythology, oral tradition, igor stravinsky, dublin, ireland, funny, personal, humor, 19th century, contemporary, modern, sarajevo.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226278599423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226278599/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles